
  <sn><md>##### Calculate the volumetric heat capacity C of a soil with a bulk density of 1.46 g/cm3 when completely dry, when completely saturated. Assume that the density of solids is 2.60 g/cm3 and that organic matter occupies 10% of the solid matter (volume). Volumetric heat capacities of mineral matter, organic matter and water are 0.48, 0.60 and 1.0 cal/cm3K respectively.


### Volumetric heat capacity of the soil

Given

* Bulk density $\rho_b = 1.46\ \mathrm{g/cm^3}$
* Particle (solid) density $\rho_s = 2.60\ \mathrm{g/cm^3}$
* Organic matter occupies 10% of the **solid** volume $so mineral = 90% of solids$
* Volumetric heat capacities: $C_{\text{mineral}}=0.48,; C_{\text{organic}}=0.60,; C_{\text{water}}=1.00) (all in (\mathrm{cal/cm^3K})$
  Formula: $C=\sum_i V_i,C_i$ where $V_i$ are volume fractions per unit bulk volume.

1. Solid volume fraction (per bulk volume):
   $$
   V_s=\frac{\rho_b}{\rho_s}=\frac{1.46}{2.60}=0.56153846
   $$
   Porosity (pore volume fraction):
   $$
   n=1-V_s=0.43846154
   $$

2. Split solids into mineral and organic (fractions of bulk volume):
   $$
   V_{\text{organic}}=0.10\cdot V_s=0.05615385
   $$
   $$
   V_{\text{mineral}}=0.90\cdot V_s=0.50538462
   $$

3. Completely dry (pores are air, negligible heat capacity):
   $$
   C_{\text{dry}}=V_{\text{mineral}}C_{\text{mineral}}+V_{\text{organic}}C_{\text{organic}}
   $$
   $$
   C_{\text{dry}}=0.50538462(0.48)+0.05615385(0.60)=0.27627692\ \mathrm{cal/cm^3K}
   $$

4. Completely saturated (pores filled with water):
   $$
   C_{\text{sat}}=V_{\text{mineral}}C_{\text{mineral}}+V_{\text{organic}}C_{\text{organic}}+n,C_{\text{water}}
   $$
   $$
   C_{\text{sat}}=0.50538462(0.48)+0.05615385(0.60)+0.43846154(1.00)=0.71473846\ \mathrm{cal/cm^3K}
   $$

Final (rounded):

* $C_{\text{dry}} \approx 0.276\ \mathrm{cal/cm^3K}$
* $C_{\text{sat}} \approx 0.715\ \mathrm{cal/cm^3K}$
