<sn><md>##### Calculate the volumetric heat capacity C of a soil with a bulk density of 1.30 g/cm3 when completely dry, when completely saturated. Assume that the density of solids is 2.60 g/cm3 and that organic matter occupies 20% of the solid matter (volume). Volumetric heat capacities of mineral matter, organic matter and water are 0.48, 0.60 and 1.0 cal/cm3K respectively.


#### Given data

- **Bulk density dry** $\rho_b = 1.30 \ \text{g/cm}^3$  
- **Particle density** $\rho_s = 2.60 \ \text{g/cm}^3$  
- Organic matter occupies **20% of the solid matter by volume**  
- Volumetric heat capacities:  
  - Mineral matter: $C_m = 0.48 \ \text{cal/cm}^3\text{K}$  
  - Organic matter: $C_o = 0.60 \ \text{cal/cm}^3\text{K}$  
  - Water: $C_w = 1.0 \ \text{cal/cm}^3\text{K}$  

---

#### Volume fractions of solids

Take **1 cm³ of total soil volume**.

Mass of solids = $1.30 \ \text{g}$.  

Volume of solids $f_s$:  
$$
f_s = \frac{\text{mass of solids}}{\rho_s} = \frac{1.30}{2.60} = 0.50 \ \text{cm}^3
$$
So porosity $\phi = 1 - f_s = 1 - 0.50 = 0.50$.

---

#### Volume fractions of mineral and organic matter in solids

Organic matter = 20% of solid volume, mineral matter = 80% of solid volume.

Thus:  
$$
f_o = 0.20 \times f_s = 0.20 \times 0.50 = 0.10 \ \text{cm}^3
$$
$$
f_m = 0.80 \times f_s = 0.80 \times 0.50 = 0.40 \ \text{cm}^3
$$

Check: $f_m + f_o = 0.50$ cm³.

---

#### Volumetric heat capacity when dry

$$
C_{\text{dry}} = f_m \times C_m + f_o \times C_o
$$
$$
C_{\text{dry}} = 0.40 \times 0.48 + 0.10 \times 0.60
$$
$$
= 0.192 + 0.06 = 0.252 \ \text{cal/cm}^3\text{K}
$$

---

#### Volumetric heat capacity when saturated

Saturated means all pore space filled with water: $\phi = 0.50$.

$$
C_{\text{sat}} = C_{\text{dry}} + \phi \times C_w
$$
$$
C_{\text{sat}} = 0.252 + 0.50 \times 1.0
$$
$$
C_{\text{sat}} = 0.252 + 0.50 = 0.752 \ \text{cal/cm}^3\text{K}
$$

---

**Final answer:**
$$
\boxed{0.252, \ 0.752}
$$
